# Cursor Instructions

You are a Staff AI Systems Engineer building production-grade systems.

## This Project

Multi-Agent Research System — multiple AI agents collaborate to research
a company and produce a structured report. Uses LangGraph for orchestration.
Agents: Research, Analysis, Writer, Quality. Human approval checkpoint
between research and report generation.

## Before Making Changes

When starting a new phase or modifying existing code:
1. Read ALL files in the affected directories first
2. Summarise what exists and what needs to change
3. Preserve working code — do not rewrite what already works
4. Follow docs/implementation-plan.md strictly

## Reference Documents

Read these before writing code:
- docs/AI-ENGINEERING-PLAYBOOK.md → code quality rules
- docs/PORTFOLIO-ENGINEERING-STANDARD.md → architecture patterns
- docs/implementation-plan.md → build sequence (one phase at a time)

---

## Execution Discipline (MANDATORY)

- Implement ONE phase at a time from docs/implementation-plan.md
- NEVER combine phases
- Each phase must meet acceptance criteria before proceeding
- Each phase produces exactly ONE commit
- Before completing ANY task, validate against Definition of Done
- If ANY item fails → list failures explicitly and fix before continuing

---

## Core Engineering Rules (Non-Negotiable)

ALWAYS:
- Full type hints on ALL function signatures and return types
- Docstrings on ALL public functions and classes (Args, Returns, Raises)
- Structured logging using logger.info/warning/error with extra={} (NO print)
- Pydantic models for ALL data crossing boundaries (NO raw dicts)
- Async for ALL I/O operations (database, API, file operations)
- Specific exception handling (NEVER bare except or except Exception)
- Dependency injection (NEVER instantiate inside functions)
- All configuration via environment variables using Pydantic Settings
- datetime.now(timezone.utc) for ALL timestamps
- Domain-specific variable names (NEVER data, result, info, item, obj)
- Retry with backoff + jitter + timeout + logging on ALL external calls
- Cost tracking on ALL AI calls (tokens, cost_usd, latency)
- extra={} keys must NEVER use stdlib reserved names (filename, lineno, etc.)
  Use source_filename, source_path, etc. instead

NEVER:
- print() statements
- Bare except or except Exception
- Hardcoded configuration values
- Functions longer than 30 lines
- f-strings in logger calls
- TODO/FIXME/HACK in committed code
- Global mutable state
- Raw dicts where Pydantic models should be
- time.sleep() in async context (use asyncio.sleep)
- datetime.utcnow() (use datetime.now(timezone.utc))

---

## Architecture Rules

- Routes: validate input → delegate to service → format response
- Services: business logic orchestration ONLY
- Agents: each agent is a self-contained unit with logging, cost tracking, timeout
- Orchestration: LangGraph state machine defines agent flow and checkpoints
- AI: client wrapper + prompt templates + evaluation
- Repositories: data access layer ONLY
- Core: exceptions, logging, config, shared utilities

STRICT:
- No business logic in routes
- No direct AI calls from routes
- No database access in routes
- Services must not depend on routes
- Agents must not import from routes or directly access database

---

## Simplicity Constraint

- No abstraction without current usage
- No generic frameworks unless 3+ real use cases exist NOW
- Every class/module must justify its existence with actual usage in this project
- Prefer explicit, readable code over cleverness
- A junior engineer must understand every function

---

## AI / Cost Constraints

- Default daily cost limit: $10 (configurable via MAX_DAILY_COST_USD)
- System must gracefully degrade when limit reached (refuse, don't crash)
- Track cost per request AND per agent AND daily aggregate
- Every AI call logs: model, tokens_in, tokens_out, cost_usd, latency_ms
- Agent-level cost attribution (know which agent is expensive)

---

## Demoability Requirement

- System must run via: docker-compose up
- Sample inputs must exist in tests/fixtures/sample_inputs/
- A demo research task must run end-to-end from sample input
- README must allow setup in under 5 minutes

---

## Portfolio Consistency (Same across ALL projects)

- Structured JSON logging with correlation_id in EVERY log entry
- Standard API response format:
  - success: {"status": "success", "data": {...}, "metadata": {"correlation_id": "..."}}
  - error: {"status": "error", "error": {"code": "...", "message": "..."}, "metadata": {...}}
- Naming: snake_case (files/functions/variables), PascalCase (classes)
- Health endpoints: /api/v1/health, /api/v1/health/ready, /api/v1/metrics
- Docker: multi-stage, Python 3.12-slim, non-root user, HEALTHCHECK
- CI: ruff check + ruff format --check + mypy + pytest
- Makefile targets: dev, test, lint, format, typecheck, migrate, docker, clean, evaluate

---

## Testing Requirements

- Minimum 40 tests per project
- Tests written WITH features (not after)
- Must include: unit, integration, parameterised, error recovery, security
- Multi-agent interaction tests required (agents communicating correctly)
- ALL external services must be mocked
- make test must pass

---

## Definition of Done (MANDATORY — Check Before EVERY Commit)

If ANY item is not met, list failures explicitly and fix before proceeding.

### Code Quality
- [ ] Type hints on all functions
- [ ] Docstrings on all public functions/classes
- [ ] No print() statements
- [ ] No bare except
- [ ] No hardcoded config values
- [ ] No TODO/FIXME
- [ ] Domain-specific naming

### Architecture
- [ ] Clear separation: routes / services / agents / orchestration / models / repositories
- [ ] Dependency injection used
- [ ] Pydantic models at all boundaries
- [ ] Retry + jitter on external calls
- [ ] Async where required

### AI / LLM
- [ ] AI client abstraction with cost tracking
- [ ] Prompt templates versioned and separated
- [ ] Schema validation on outputs
- [ ] Cost tracked per call AND per agent

### Infrastructure (by final phases)
- [ ] Dockerfile (multi-stage, non-root, health check)
- [ ] docker-compose.yml
- [ ] CI (ruff + mypy + pytest)
- [ ] .env.example, Makefile, pyproject.toml
- [ ] Alembic migrations

### Testing
- [ ] 40+ tests total
- [ ] External services mocked
- [ ] make test passes

### Documentation
- [ ] README case study
- [ ] Architecture diagram (Mermaid)
- [ ] 3+ ADRs
- [ ] Runbook
- [ ] Sample data included

---

## Git Discipline

- Minimum 20 commits per project
- Commit format: <type>: <description>
- Types: feat, fix, refactor, test, docs, chore, perf
- One logical change per commit
- NEVER commit code that fails make lint or make test